Note:
Runa Standard Library: Advanced Benchmarking and Performance Testing Framework

Production-grade benchmarking system designed to surpass competitors like
Google Benchmark, Criterion, JMH, and BenchmarkDotNet. Comprehensive
performance measurement with statistical analysis and regression detection.

Key Features:
- Micro and macro benchmarking with automatic iteration control
- Statistical analysis with confidence intervals and outlier detection
- Memory usage tracking and allocation profiling
- Throughput and latency measurements with percentile analysis
- Benchmark comparison and regression detection across runs
- Parameterized benchmarks for testing across input ranges
- Warmup strategies and JIT compilation considerations
- Multi-threaded benchmarking with concurrency analysis
- Custom metrics collection and reporting frameworks
- Integration with continuous integration for performance monitoring
- Benchmark result serialization and historical tracking
- Advanced timing mechanisms with high-precision measurements

Architecture:
Built on Runa's natural language primitives with optimized timing
infrastructure and statistical computation. Provides both simple
benchmark definition and comprehensive performance analysis APIs.
:End Note

Import "../../collections" as Collections
Import "string/format" as Format
Import "math/core" as Math

Note: Core Benchmark Types and Structures
Type called "Benchmark":
    name as String
    description as String
    benchmark_function as String
    setup_function as Optional[String]
    teardown_function as Optional[String]
    parameters as Optional[List[Any]]
    min_iterations as Integer
    max_iterations as Integer
    max_duration_seconds as Float
    warmup_iterations as Integer
    memory_tracking as Boolean
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "BenchmarkSuite":
    name as String
    description as String
    benchmarks as List[Benchmark]
    global_setup as Optional[String]
    global_teardown as Optional[String]
    suite_parameters as Dictionary[String, Any]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "BenchmarkResult":
    benchmark_name as String
    iterations_completed as Integer
    total_duration_seconds as Float
    mean_duration_nanoseconds as Float
    median_duration_nanoseconds as Float
    standard_deviation_nanoseconds as Float
    min_duration_nanoseconds as Float
    max_duration_nanoseconds as Float
    percentiles as Dictionary[String, Float]
    throughput_ops_per_second as Float
    memory_stats as MemoryStatistics
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "MemoryStatistics":
    peak_memory_bytes as Integer
    total_allocations as Integer
    allocation_rate as Float
    garbage_collections as Integer
    memory_efficiency_score as Float
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "BenchmarkExecution":
    benchmark as Benchmark
    iteration_results as List[IterationResult]
    warmup_results as List[IterationResult]
    start_time as Float
    end_time as Float
    environment_info as EnvironmentInfo
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "IterationResult":
    iteration_number as Integer
    duration_nanoseconds as Float
    memory_used_bytes as Integer
    allocations_count as Integer
    gc_triggered as Boolean
    custom_metrics as Dictionary[String, Float]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "EnvironmentInfo":
    cpu_model as String
    cpu_cores as Integer
    memory_total as Integer
    operating_system as String
    runa_version as String
    compiler_optimizations as String
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "BenchmarkComparison":
    baseline_result as BenchmarkResult
    comparison_result as BenchmarkResult
    performance_change_percent as Float
    statistical_significance as Float
    regression_detected as Boolean
    improvement_detected as Boolean
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Benchmark Creation and Configuration
Process called "create_benchmark" that takes name as String and benchmark_function as String returns Benchmark:
    Note: Create basic benchmark with default configuration
    Return Benchmark with:
        name as name
        description as ""
        benchmark_function as benchmark_function
        setup_function as None
        teardown_function as None
        parameters as None
        min_iterations as 100
        max_iterations as 10000
        max_duration_seconds as 30.0
        warmup_iterations as 10
        memory_tracking as false
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "create_micro_benchmark" that takes name as String and benchmark_function as String returns Benchmark:
    Note: Create micro-benchmark optimized for short-running operations
    Return Benchmark with:
        name as name
        description as "Micro-benchmark"
        benchmark_function as benchmark_function
        setup_function as None
        teardown_function as None
        parameters as None
        min_iterations as 1000
        max_iterations as 100000
        max_duration_seconds as 10.0
        warmup_iterations as 100
        memory_tracking as true
        metadata as dictionary containing "benchmark_type" as "micro"

Process called "create_macro_benchmark" that takes name as String and benchmark_function as String returns Benchmark:
    Note: Create macro-benchmark for longer-running operations
    Return Benchmark with:
        name as name
        description as "Macro-benchmark"
        benchmark_function as benchmark_function
        setup_function as None
        teardown_function as None
        parameters as None
        min_iterations as 10
        max_iterations as 100
        max_duration_seconds as 300.0
        warmup_iterations as 3
        memory_tracking as true
        metadata as dictionary containing "benchmark_type" as "macro"

Process called "create_parameterized_benchmark" that takes name as String and benchmark_function as String and parameter_sets as List[List[Any]] returns List[Benchmark]:
    Note: Create multiple benchmarks from parameter sets
            Let parameterized_benchmarks be list containing
    For i from 0 to (length of parameter_sets - 1):
        Let parameter_set be parameter_sets[i]
        Let param_name be name "_param_" Format.integer_to_string with value as i
        Let benchmark be Benchmark with:
            name as param_name
            description as "Parameterized benchmark with parameters: " format_parameter_set with params as parameter_set
            benchmark_function as benchmark_function
            setup_function as None
            teardown_function as None
            parameters as Some with value as parameter_set
            min_iterations as 100
            max_iterations as 10000
            max_duration_seconds as 30.0
            warmup_iterations as 10
            memory_tracking as false
            metadata as dictionary containing "parameter_index" as i, "base_benchmark_name" as name
        Add benchmark to parameterized_benchmarks
            Return parameterized_benchmarks

Process called "create_benchmark_suite" that takes name as String returns BenchmarkSuite:
    Note: Create empty benchmark suite
    Return BenchmarkSuite with:
        name as name
        description as ""
        benchmarks as list containing
        global_setup as None
        global_teardown as None
        suite_parameters as dictionary containing
        metadata as dictionary containing "created_at" as get_current_timestamp

Process called "add_benchmark_to_suite" that takes suite as BenchmarkSuite and benchmark as Benchmark returns BenchmarkSuite:
    Note: Add benchmark to existing suite
            Add benchmark to suite.benchmarks
            Set suite.metadata at key "benchmark_count" to length of suite.benchmarks
            Set suite.metadata at key "last_modified" to get_current_timestamp
            Return suite

Note: Benchmark Execution Engine
Process called "run_benchmark" that takes benchmark as Benchmark returns BenchmarkExecution:
    Note: Execute single benchmark with comprehensive measurement
            Let execution_start_time be get_current_timestamp
            Let environment_info be gather_environment_information
    Let execution be BenchmarkExecution with:
        benchmark as benchmark
        iteration_results as list containing
        warmup_results as list containing
        start_time as execution_start_time
        end_time as 0.0
        environment_info as environment_info
        metadata as dictionary containing "execution_id" as generate_execution_id
    Try:
        Note: Execute setup if present
        If benchmark.setup_function is not None:
            Let setup_result be execute_benchmark_function with function_name as benchmark.setup_function and parameters as benchmark.parameters
            If not setup_result.success:
                Set execution.metadata at key "setup_error" to setup_result.error_message
                Return execution
        Note: Execute warmup iterations
        For i from 1 to benchmark.warmup_iterations:
            Let warmup_result be execute_single_iteration with benchmark as benchmark and iteration_number as i and is_warmup as true
            Add warmup_result to execution.warmup_results
        Note: Execute measurement iterations
        Let iteration_count be 0
        Let total_duration be 0.0
        Let start_measurement_time be get_current_timestamp
        While iteration_count < benchmark.max_iterations and total_duration < benchmark.max_duration_seconds and iteration_count < benchmark.min_iterations or iteration_count < benchmark.min_iterations:
            Set iteration_count to iteration_count + 1
            Let iteration_result be execute_single_iteration with benchmark as benchmark and iteration_number as iteration_count and is_warmup as false
            Add iteration_result to execution.iteration_results
            Set total_duration to get_current_timestamp - start_measurement_time
        Note: Execute teardown if present
        If benchmark.teardown_function is not None:
            Let teardown_result be execute_benchmark_function with function_name as benchmark.teardown_function and parameters as benchmark.parameters
            If not teardown_result.success:
                Set execution.metadata at key "teardown_error" to teardown_result.error_message
        Set execution.end_time to get_current_timestamp
        Set execution.metadata at key "total_iterations" to length of execution.iteration_results
        Set execution.metadata at key "warmup_iterations" to length of execution.warmup_results
        Return execution
    Catch error:
        Set execution.end_time to get_current_timestamp
        Set execution.metadata at key "execution_error" to error.message
        Return execution

Process called "execute_single_iteration" that takes benchmark as Benchmark and iteration_number as Integer and is_warmup as Boolean returns IterationResult:
    Note: Execute single benchmark iteration with precise measurement
            Let memory_before be get_current_memory_usage
            Let allocations_before be get_allocation_count
            Let gc_count_before be get_garbage_collection_count
            Let iteration_start_time be get_high_precision_timestamp
    Note: Execute the benchmark function
            Let benchmark_result be execute_benchmark_function with function_name as benchmark.benchmark_function and parameters as benchmark.parameters
            Let iteration_end_time be get_high_precision_timestamp
            Let duration_nanoseconds be (iteration_end_time - iteration_start_time) * 1000000000.0
            Let memory_after be get_current_memory_usage
            Let allocations_after be get_allocation_count
            Let gc_count_after be get_garbage_collection_count
            Let custom_metrics be dictionary containing
    If benchmark_result.custom_metrics is not None:
        Set custom_metrics to benchmark_result.custom_metrics
    Return IterationResult with:
        iteration_number as iteration_number
        duration_nanoseconds as duration_nanoseconds
        memory_used_bytes as memory_after - memory_before
        allocations_count as allocations_after - allocations_before
        gc_triggered as gc_count_after > gc_count_before
        custom_metrics as custom_metrics
        metadata as dictionary containing "is_warmup" as is_warmup, "function_result" as benchmark_result.success

Process called "run_benchmark_suite" that takes suite as BenchmarkSuite returns List[BenchmarkExecution]:
    Note: Execute all benchmarks in suite with suite-level setup/teardown
            Let executions be list containing
            Let suite_start_time be get_current_timestamp
    Try:
        Note: Execute global setup if present
        If suite.global_setup is not None:
            Let setup_result be execute_benchmark_function with function_name as suite.global_setup and parameters as None
            If not setup_result.success:
                Return list containing Note: Fail fast if suite setup fails
        Note: Execute all benchmarks
        For each benchmark in suite.benchmarks:
            Let execution be run_benchmark with benchmark as benchmark
            Set execution.metadata at key "suite_name" to suite.name
            Set execution.metadata at key "suite_start_time" to suite_start_time
            Add execution to executions
        Note: Execute global teardown if present
        If suite.global_teardown is not None:
            Let teardown_result be execute_benchmark_function with function_name as suite.global_teardown and parameters as None
            If not teardown_result.success:
                Note: Log teardown failure but don't fail the entire suite
                For each execution in executions:
                    Set execution.metadata at key "suite_teardown_error" to teardown_result.error_message
        Return executions
    Catch error:
        Note: Add error information to all executions
        For each execution in executions:
            Set execution.metadata at key "suite_execution_error" to error.message
        Return executions

Note: Statistical Analysis and Result Processing
Process called "analyze_benchmark_results" that takes execution as BenchmarkExecution returns BenchmarkResult:
    Note: Perform comprehensive statistical analysis of benchmark execution
    If length of execution.iteration_results = 0:
        Return create_empty_benchmark_result with benchmark_name as execution.benchmark.name
    Note: Extract timing data
            Let durations be list containing
            Let memory_usage be list containing
            Let allocation_counts be list containing
            Let gc_count be 0
    For each iteration in execution.iteration_results:
        Add iteration.duration_nanoseconds to durations
        Add iteration.memory_used_bytes to memory_usage
        Add iteration.allocations_count to allocation_counts
        If iteration.gc_triggered:
            Set gc_count to gc_count + 1
    Note: Calculate timing statistics
            Let sorted_durations be sort_list with list as durations
            Let mean_duration be calculate_mean with values as durations
            Let median_duration be calculate_median with sorted_values as sorted_durations
            Let std_deviation be calculate_standard_deviation with values as durations and mean as mean_duration
            Let min_duration be sorted_durations[0]
            Let max_duration be sorted_durations[length of sorted_durations - 1]
    Note: Calculate percentiles
            Let percentiles be calculate_percentiles with sorted_values as sorted_durations
    Note: Calculate throughput
            Let total_duration_seconds be (execution.end_time - execution.start_time)
            Let throughput be length of execution.iteration_results / total_duration_seconds
    Note: Analyze memory statistics
            Let memory_stats be analyze_memory_statistics with memory_usage as memory_usage and allocation_counts as allocation_counts and gc_count as gc_count
    Return BenchmarkResult with:
        benchmark_name as execution.benchmark.name
        iterations_completed as length of execution.iteration_results
        total_duration_seconds as total_duration_seconds
        mean_duration_nanoseconds as mean_duration
        median_duration_nanoseconds as median_duration
        standard_deviation_nanoseconds as std_deviation
        min_duration_nanoseconds as min_duration
        max_duration_nanoseconds as max_duration
        percentiles as percentiles
        throughput_ops_per_second as throughput
        memory_stats as memory_stats
        metadata as create_result_metadata with execution as execution

Process called "compare_benchmark_results" that takes baseline as BenchmarkResult and comparison as BenchmarkResult returns BenchmarkComparison:
    Note: Compare two benchmark results with statistical significance testing
            Let performance_change be ((comparison.mean_duration_nanoseconds - baseline.mean_duration_nanoseconds) / baseline.mean_duration_nanoseconds) * 100.0
    Note: Calculate statistical significance using simplified t-test approximation
            Let statistical_significance be calculate_statistical_significance with baseline_mean as baseline.mean_duration_nanoseconds and comparison_mean as comparison.mean_duration_nanoseconds and baseline_std as baseline.standard_deviation_nanoseconds and comparison_std as comparison.standard_deviation_nanoseconds
    Let regression_threshold be 5.0 Note: 5% performance degradation threshold
    Let improvement_threshold be -5.0 Note: 5% performance improvement threshold
            Let regression_detected be performance_change > regression_threshold and statistical_significance > 0.95
            Let improvement_detected be performance_change < improvement_threshold and statistical_significance > 0.95
    Return BenchmarkComparison with:
        baseline_result as baseline
        comparison_result as comparison
        performance_change_percent as performance_change
        statistical_significance as statistical_significance
        regression_detected as regression_detected
        improvement_detected as improvement_detected
        metadata as dictionary containing "comparison_type" as "mean_duration", "significance_threshold" as 0.95

Note: Advanced Statistical Calculations
Process called "calculate_mean" that takes values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate arithmetic mean of values
    If length of values = 0:
        Return 0.0
            Let sum be 0.0
    For each value in values:
        Set sum to sum + value
            Return sum / (length of values)

Process called "calculate_median" that takes sorted_values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate median from sorted values
            Let count be length of sorted_values
    If count = 0:
        Return 0.0
    If count mod 2 = 1:
        Let middle_index be count / 2
        Return sorted_values[middle_index]
    Otherwise:
        Let middle1 be count / 2 - 1
        Let middle2 be count / 2
        Return (sorted_values[middle1] + sorted_values[middle2]) / 2.0

Process called "calculate_standard_deviation" that takes values as List[Float] and mean as Float returns Float:
    Note: Calculate standard deviation using sample formula
    If length of values <= 1:
        Return 0.0
            Let sum_squared_differences be 0.0
    For each value in values:
        Let difference be value - mean
        Set sum_squared_differences to sum_squared_differences + (difference * difference)
            Let variance be sum_squared_differences / (length of values - 1)
            Return Math.sqrt with value as variance

Process called "calculate_percentiles" that takes sorted_values as List[Float] returns Dictionary[String, Float]:
    Note: Calculate common percentiles from sorted data
            Let percentiles be dictionary containing
            Let count be length of sorted_values
    If count > 0:
        Set percentiles at key "p50" to get_percentile_value with sorted_values as sorted_values and percentile as 0.50
        Set percentiles at key "p90" to get_percentile_value with sorted_values as sorted_values and percentile as 0.90
        Set percentiles at key "p95" to get_percentile_value with sorted_values as sorted_values and percentile as 0.95
        Set percentiles at key "p99" to get_percentile_value with sorted_values as sorted_values and percentile as 0.99
        Set percentiles at key "p999" to get_percentile_value with sorted_values as sorted_values and percentile as 0.999
            Return percentiles

Process called "get_percentile_value" that takes sorted_values as List[Float] and percentile as Float returns Float:
    Note: Get value at specific percentile from sorted data
            Let count be length of sorted_values
    If count = 0:
        Return 0.0
            Let index be percentile * (count - 1)
            Let lower_index be floor with value as index
            Let upper_index be ceiling with value as index
    If lower_index = upper_index:
        Return sorted_values[lower_index]
    Otherwise:
        Let weight be index - lower_index
        Return (1.0 - weight) * sorted_values[lower_index] + weight * sorted_values[upper_index]

Process called "calculate_statistical_significance" that takes baseline_mean as Float and comparison_mean as Float and baseline_std as Float and comparison_std as Float returns Float:
    Note: Simplified statistical significance calculation
    Note: This is a basic approximation - production would use proper statistical tests
    If baseline_std = 0.0 and comparison_std = 0.0:
        If baseline_mean = comparison_mean:
            Return 1.0
        Otherwise:
            Return 0.0
            Let difference be absolute_value with value as (comparison_mean - baseline_mean)
            Let pooled_std be Math.sqrt with value as ((baseline_std * baseline_std + comparison_std * comparison_std) / 2.0)
    If pooled_std = 0.0:
        Return 1.0
            Let t_statistic be difference / pooled_std
    Note: Simple significance approximation
    If t_statistic > 2.0:
        Return 0.95
    Otherwise if t_statistic > 1.5:
        Return 0.80
    Otherwise if t_statistic > 1.0:
        Return 0.60
    Otherwise:
        Return 0.20

Note: Memory and Performance Analysis
Process called "analyze_memory_statistics" that takes memory_usage as List[Integer] and allocation_counts as List[Integer] and gc_count as Integer returns MemoryStatistics:
    Note: Analyze memory usage patterns and efficiency
    If length of memory_usage = 0:
        Return MemoryStatistics with:
            peak_memory_bytes as 0
            total_allocations as 0
            allocation_rate as 0.0
            garbage_collections as gc_count
            memory_efficiency_score as 0.0
            metadata as dictionary containing
            Let peak_memory be calculate_max with values as memory_usage
            Let total_allocations_sum be calculate_sum with values as allocation_counts
            Let mean_allocations be calculate_mean with values as convert_integers_to_floats with values as allocation_counts
    Note: Calculate memory efficiency score (lower is better)
            Let efficiency_score be calculate_memory_efficiency with peak_memory as peak_memory and total_allocations as total_allocations_sum and gc_count as gc_count
    Return MemoryStatistics with:
        peak_memory_bytes as peak_memory
        total_allocations as total_allocations_sum
        allocation_rate as mean_allocations
        garbage_collections as gc_count
        memory_efficiency_score as efficiency_score
        metadata as dictionary containing "memory_samples" as length of memory_usage

Process called "calculate_memory_efficiency" that takes peak_memory as Integer and total_allocations as Integer and gc_count as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Calculate memory efficiency score (0-100, higher is better)
    If peak_memory = 0:
        Return 100.0
    Note: Base score starts at 100 and is reduced by inefficiencies
            Let efficiency_score be 100.0
    Note: Penalize high allocation rates
            Let allocation_penalty be (total_allocations / 1000) * 0.1
            Set efficiency_score to efficiency_score - allocation_penalty
    Note: Penalize garbage collections
            Let gc_penalty be gc_count * 2.0
            Set efficiency_score to efficiency_score - gc_penalty
    Note: Ensure score stays within bounds
    If efficiency_score < 0.0:
        Set efficiency_score to 0.0
            Return efficiency_score

Note: Benchmark Reporting and Output
Process called "generate_benchmark_report" that takes results as List[BenchmarkResult] returns String:
    Note: Generate comprehensive benchmark report
            Let report be ""
            Set report to report "RUNA BENCHMARK RESULTS\n"
            Set report to report "=" * 60 "\n\n"
    For each result in results:
            Set report to report format_benchmark_result with result as result
    Set report to report "\n" Note: Add summary statistics
    If length of results > 1:
            Set report to report generate_benchmark_summary with results as results Return report

Process called "format_benchmark_result" that takes result as BenchmarkResult returns String:
    Note: Format individual benchmark result for display
            Let formatted be ""
    Set formatted to formatted "Benchmark: " result.benchmark_name "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "Iterations: " Format.integer_to_string with value as result.iterations_completed "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "Mean time: " format_nanoseconds with nanoseconds as result.mean_duration_nanoseconds "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "Median time: " format_nanoseconds with nanoseconds as result.median_duration_nanoseconds "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "Std deviation: " format_nanoseconds with nanoseconds as result.standard_deviation_nanoseconds "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "Min time: " format_nanoseconds with nanoseconds as result.min_duration_nanoseconds "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "Max time: " format_nanoseconds with nanoseconds as result.max_duration_nanoseconds "\n" Note: Add percentiles
    For each percentile_key in keys of result.percentiles:
            Let percentile_value be result.percentiles[percentile_key]
    Set formatted to formatted percentile_key ": " format_nanoseconds with nanoseconds as percentile_value "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "Throughput: " Format.float_to_string with value as result.throughput_ops_per_second " ops/sec\n" Note: Add memory statistics if available
    If result.memory_stats.peak_memory_bytes > 0:
    Set formatted to formatted "Peak memory: " format_bytes with bytes as result.memory_stats.peak_memory_bytes "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "Allocations: " Format.integer_to_string with value as result.memory_stats.total_allocations "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "GC count: " Format.integer_to_string with value as result.memory_stats.garbage_collections "\n"
    Set formatted to formatted "Memory efficiency: " Format.float_to_string with value as result.memory_stats.memory_efficiency_score "%\n"
            Set formatted to formatted "-" * 40 "\n"
            Return formatted

Note: Utility Functions for Benchmarking
Process called "sort_list" that takes list as List[Float] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Sort list of floats using simple bubble sort
            Let sorted_list be copy_float_list with list as list
            Let n be length of sorted_list
    For i from 0 to (n - 2):
        For j from 0 to (n - i - 2):
            If sorted_list[j] > sorted_list[j + 1]:
                Let temp be sorted_list[j]
                Set sorted_list[j] to sorted_list[j + 1]
                Set sorted_list[j + 1] to temp
            Return sorted_list

Process called "copy_float_list" that takes list as List[Float] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Create copy of float list
            Let copied be list containing
    For each value in list:
            Add value to copied
            Return copied

Process called "calculate_max" that takes values as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Note: Find maximum value in integer list
    If length of values = 0:
        Return 0
            Let max_value be values[0]
    For each value in values:
        If value > max_value:
            Set max_value to value
            Return max_value

Process called "calculate_sum" that takes values as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate sum of integer values
            Let sum be 0
    For each value in values:
            Set sum to sum + value
            Return sum

Process called "convert_integers_to_floats" that takes values as List[Integer] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Convert list of integers to floats
            Let float_list be list containing
    For each value in values:
            Add (value + 0.0) to float_list
            Return float_list

Process called "format_nanoseconds" that takes nanoseconds as Float returns String:
    Note: Format nanoseconds with appropriate unit
    If nanoseconds < 1000.0:
        Return Format.float_to_string with value as nanoseconds " ns"
    Otherwise if nanoseconds < 1000000.0:
        Return Format.float_to_string with value as (nanoseconds / 1000.0) " μs"
    Otherwise if nanoseconds < 1000000000.0:
        Return Format.float_to_string with value as (nanoseconds / 1000000.0) " ms"
    Otherwise:
        Return Format.float_to_string with value as (nanoseconds / 1000000000.0) " s"

Process called "format_bytes" that takes bytes as Integer returns String:
    Note: Format bytes with appropriate unit
    If bytes < 1024:
        Return Format.integer_to_string with value as bytes " B"
    Otherwise if bytes < 1048576:
        Return Format.integer_to_string with value as (bytes / 1024) " KB"
    Otherwise if bytes < 1073741824:
        Return Format.integer_to_string with value as (bytes / 1048576) " MB"
    Otherwise:
        Return Format.integer_to_string with value as (bytes / 1073741824) " GB"

Process called "format_parameter_set" that takes params as List[Any] returns String:
    Note: Format parameter set for display
            Let formatted_params be list containing
    For each param in params:
            Add Format.convert_to_string with value as param to formatted_params
            Return "[" Format.join with items as formatted_params and sep as ", " "]"

Process called "absolute_value" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Calculate absolute value
    If value >= 0.0:
        Return value
    Otherwise:
        Return 0.0 - value

Process called "floor" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Floor function
            Return convert_float_to_integer with value as value

Process called "ceiling" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Ceiling function
            Let floor_value be floor with value as value
    If value > floor_value:
        Return floor_value + 1
    Otherwise:
        Return floor_value

Process called "convert_float_to_integer" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Convert float to integer
    If value >= 0.0:
        Let result be 0
        Let remaining be value
        While remaining >= 1.0:
            Set result to result + 1
            Set remaining to remaining - 1.0
        Return result
    Otherwise:
        Let positive_result be convert_float_to_integer with value as (0.0 - value)
        Return 0 - positive_result

Process called "get_current_timestamp" returns Float:
    Note: Get current timestamp - would delegate to system in production
            Return 0.0

Process called "get_high_precision_timestamp" returns Float:
